The Economy of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in SYRIA, in the UKRAINE, and elsewhere are constantly a topic in the news, and therefore many would probably say WAR.
That proves to be a great misconception.
The right answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It is obvious that every person would like to end each WAR and violence, just as we would like to bring an end to poverty, hunger, and global warming and provide access to education for all people.
However, given the preceding context, the translation of the current source sentence would be more consistent if it matches the style of the previous translations. 
We must set priorities and for that one can apply an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals they consider the most sensible from their perspective.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the expenditure of resources that would otherwise, for example, be used to combat hunger?
And if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon of Stanford University and Anke Höffler of the Centre for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society – murders and especially violence against women and children – poses a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die from interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who are killed, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries record murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
One murder in America costs a person their life and society $9.1 million.
Measured globally, this form of violent crime costs 1.7% of the world's gross domestic product (GDP).
It is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be eradicated, societies around the world would be better off in a way that could be quantified at 1.7% of the GDP.
Compare this to the significantly lower costs of civil wars, which correspond to around 0.2% of global GDP.
That is still much less than the greatest source of violence overall: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence at the hands of their partners or family members last year.
Women who were beaten, forcibly married at a young age, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and mutilated suffered as a result.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs alone of violence by partners amount to 4.4 trillion dollars or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is the abuse of children, 80% of which is committed by parents.
The definition of child abuse varies from culture to culture, but approximately 15% of children experience each month what the UN classifies as severe physical punishment.
Women who suffer from blows to the face, head, or ears are among those affected. A quarter of these children are repeatedly and as severely as possible beaten with an object.
This suffering occurs every month among approximately 290 million children.
The societal costs amount to 3.6 trillion dollars or 4.2% of the global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid is currently being directed towards reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals are screaming for action to be taken.
Unfortunately, there is still a lack of secure knowledge on where the limited funds should be used most effectively.
One thing that is clear is that the money being spent to reduce violence could be used more effectively.
Large sums of aid money are earmarked for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component of crime prevention.
Other programs may make an indirect contribution, but it is apparent that much could be done better.
Some solutions, as clear as it is, work very well.
More effective social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve the quality of life for children and their physical and mental well-being, and lower the costs of care and procedural costs.
One dollar spent on this program generates a benefit worth 14 dollars: it is thus an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes need to change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda called SASA! is underway.
(Swahili for "Now!") has been working to promote the idea that violence in the partnership is unacceptable and has contributed to a halving of the number of cases.
That is a fantastic result, even though no cost-efficiency analysis is available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach – a time limit for the sale of alcohol, the recovery of public space, and improvements in the police and justice system – the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
That is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many physical attacks and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability may be of crucial importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on more effective enforcement of existing regulations has shown that physical attacks can be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with a benefit-to-cost ratio of 17:1.
We still don't know enough, but two points are clear: first, domestic violence against women and children costs society an estimated $8 trillion per year, making it a huge – and woefully underappreciated – global issue.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
Therefore, reducing domestic violence should be a priority for the world's next development goals.
